  "prompt": "What is the difference between Nizams and the Mughals? Who were relatively more powerful in the 18th Century?",
  "response": "The Nizams and the Mughals were distinct entities in the history of India, each with its own origin, territory, and influence.\n\n**Nizams:**\n- The Nizams were the rulers of the princely state of Hyderabad in South India.\n- The title \"Nizam\" was first used by Nizam-ul-Mulk Asaf Jah, who founded the Asaf Jahi dynasty in the early 18th century after the decline of Mughal power.\n- The Nizams were originally appointed as governors under the Mughal Empire but gained independence as the empire weakened.\n- They ruled Hyderabad from 1724 until the merger of the state with India in 1948.\n\n**Mughals:**\n- The Mughal Empire was founded by Babur in 1526 and became one of the largest and most influential empires in Indian history.\n- It reached its zenith under emperors like Akbar, Jahangir, Shah Jahan, and Aurangzeb.\n- The Mughal Empire began to decline in the late 17th century and faced significant challenges in the 18th century, including invasions, internal conflicts, and the rise of regional powers.\n\n**Relative Power in the 18th Century:**\n- In the early 18th century, the Mughal Empire was still a significant force, but its power was rapidly diminishing, particularly after the death of Aurangzeb in 1707.\n- The empire faced invasions from the Persian ruler Nader Shah and the Afghan ruler Ahmad Shah Abdali, which further weakened its hold.\n- Regional powers like the Marathas, the Sikhs, and the Nizams began to assert their independence and control over territories.\n- The Nizams of Hyderabad gained considerable autonomy and power during this period, especially under the leadership of Nizam-ul-Mulk Asaf Jah I.\n- By the mid-18th century, the Nizams were relatively more powerful in their region compared to the weakened Mughal central authority.\n\nIn summary, while the Mughals were historically more powerful and influential, by the 18th century, the Nizams had become relatively more powerful in their region due to the decline of the Mughal Empire.",
